{
  "texts": [
    "This is attributable to the inherent complexity of testing itself.",
    "Approaching testing as \"exhaustive,\" meant to cover all paths in the code or all possible input data, has highlighted that achieving complete software testing is impossible under these conditions.",
    "The sheer volume of potential input data, code execution paths, and system states is immense, rendering \"exhaustive\" testing theoretically impossible.",
    "As a result, in testing, it's necessary to establish a \"stopping criterion,\" reaching which is regarded as a tradeoff between achieving as comprehensive testing as possible and the resources allocated for testing within the project's scope.",
    "However, the task of testing a project remains complex and unattainable in its entirety."
  ]
}